#### James Goodnight

*   **Born:** James Howard Goodnight
    January 6, 1943 (age 82)
    [Salisbury, North Carolina](/Salisbury,_North_Carolina), U.S.
*   **Other names:** Jim Goodnight
*   **Education:** [North Carolina State University](/North_Carolina_State_University) (PhD)
*   **Occupations:** Businessman and software developer
*   **Title:** Co-founder & CEO, [SAS](/SAS_Institute)
*   **Term:** 1976–present
*   **Spouse:** Ann Goodnight
*   **Children:** 3

James Howard Goodnight, born on January 6, 1943, is an American [billionaire](/Billionaire) businessman and a software developer of considerable repute. He has held the position of CEO at [SAS](/SAS_Institute) since its inception in 1976, an enterprise he co-founded with a group of fellow faculty members from [North Carolina State University](/North_Carolina_State_University). As of early 2025, his net worth was estimated by the [Bloomberg Billionaires Index](/Bloomberg_Billionaires_Index) to be a staggering US$18.5 billion. He is widely acknowledged as the wealthiest individual in [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), a testament to his enduring success.

#### Early life and career

Born in [Salisbury, North Carolina](/Salisbury,_North_Carolina), to Albert and Dorothy Goodnight, James Howard Goodnight’s early years were spent in [Greensboro](/Greensboro,_North_Carolina) until the age of twelve. The family then relocated to [Wilmington](/Wilmington,_North_Carolina). Even as a child, he was no stranger to hard work, contributing to his father's hardware store.

His initial foray into the world of computing occurred during his studies at [North Carolina State University](/North_Carolina_State_University), where he took a Mathematics course. During one summer, he secured employment writing software programs for the agricultural economics department. It’s worth noting that Goodnight was also a member of the Beta-Beta chapter of [Tau Kappa Epsilon](/Tau_Kappa_Epsilon) at NC State, even contributing to the construction of a new fraternity house for the chapter in 2002.

In 1968, Goodnight obtained a master's degree in statistics. His professional journey also led him to a company involved in building electronic equipment for the [Apollo](/Apollo) space capsules' ground stations. This experience, marked by a high employee turnover rate, significantly shaped his later perspectives on corporate culture. Following his work on the Apollo project, Goodnight returned to North Carolina State University, where he pursued and earned a PhD in statistics. He remained a faculty member there from 1972 to 1976.

#### Career

##### Creation of SAS at NCSU

While still affiliated with North Carolina State University, Goodnight embarked on a collaborative effort with fellow faculty member [Anthony James Barr](/Anthony_James_Barr). Their joint leadership on a research project aimed to develop a comprehensive statistical analysis system – the very origin of the name [SAS](/SAS_(software)) – specifically for analyzing agricultural data. This ambitious project was supported by a consortium of eight land-grant universities and received substantial funding from the [USDA](/USDA). [John Sall](/John_Sall) joined this pivotal project in 1973, further solidifying the foundation of what would become a technological titan.

##### Founding SAS Institute

By 1976, the statistical software had garnered a customer base of 100, prompting Goodnight to make the decisive move to establish a private company. Alongside Sall, Barr, and [Jane Helwig](/Jane_Helwig), Goodnight departed from NCSU to found [SAS Institute](/SAS_Institute). Their initial operational base was a modest office situated directly across the street from the university.

The burgeoning success of SAS led to its rapid expansion. By 1979, the company had outgrown its original premises in Raleigh. Goodnight expressed a desire for a more "serene" environment, away from the bustle of the city. This led the team to select [Cary, North Carolina](/Cary,_North_Carolina) as their new home. The SAS Institute officially relocated to a new, larger office in Cary in 1980, marking a significant milestone in its growth trajectory.

##### Growth and expansion

Remarkably, as of 2025, James Goodnight has maintained his role as CEO of SAS Institute for nearly five decades. Under his unwavering leadership, the company has experienced a trajectory of continuous and substantial growth. Its annual revenue saw a dramatic increase, climbing from $138,000 in its inaugural year to an impressive $420 million by 1993, and further escalating to $3.2 billion by 2022.

SAS stands today as one of the largest privately held software providers globally. The company is renowned for its development of sophisticated software suites encompassing statistical analysis, [machine learning](/Machine_learning), [deep learning](/Deep_learning), [computer vision](/Computer_vision), and [natural language processing](/Natural_language_processing). Notable among its offerings are SAS itself, [JMP](/JMP_(statistical_software)), and the advanced analytics platform [SAS Viya](/SAS_Viya).

The SAS campus in Cary has transformed into a sprawling complex, now encompassing 900 acres. Approximately 4,000 of the company's 10,000 employees are based at this central hub.

Throughout the majority of SAS's history, Goodnight steadfastly rejected acquisition offers and opted against taking the company public. This deliberate decision was rooted in his desire to preserve the unique work environment and culture he had cultivated. However, since 2021, Goodnight has been actively steering the company through preparations for an [initial public offering](/Initial_public_offering) (IPO). This planned transition is intended to enable the company to offer stock options to its employees and enhance its overall public profile.

#### Leadership style

James Goodnight is widely credited with architecting SAS's distinctive corporate culture, a milieu frequently characterized by the media as "utopian." From the company's nascent stages, Goodnight championed a flat and remarkably flexible organizational structure. In the early years, he introduced a suite of progressive benefits, including profit sharing, a standard 35-hour work week, on-site medical facilities, childcare services, and a host of other employee-centric amenities. These initiatives were instrumental in fostering enhanced productivity and ensuring remarkable employee retention rates.

The publication *HSM Global* encapsulated Goodnight's leadership philosophy within a framework of three core tenets: firstly, to empower employees to perform at their best by providing intellectual challenges and diligently removing obstacles; secondly, to hold managers accountable for igniting creativity within their teams; and thirdly, to dismantle arbitrary distinctions between different roles within the company, fostering a sense of unity. Furthermore, he emphasized engaging customers as active partners in the creative process, thereby contributing to the delivery of superior products.

#### Awards and recognition

In 1981, Goodnight was honored with election as a [Fellow of the American Statistical Association](/Fellow_of_the_American_Statistical_Association), a significant acknowledgment of his contributions to the field. He has also earned the moniker "Godfather of AI" for his foundational role in the creation of SAS, a system that has profoundly impacted the field of [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence).

His accolades continued in 1997 when he received the Golden Plate Award from the [American Academy of Achievement](/Academy_of_Achievement). In 2004, *Harvard Business School* recognized him as a Great American Business Leader, and *Inc. Magazine* named him one of America's 25 Most Fascinating Entrepreneurs. Goodnight has also been a consistent and valued participant and speaker at the prestigious [World Economic Forum](/World_Economic_Forum). In March 2020, he was presented with a CEO Great Place to Work For All Leadership Award by Great Place to Work.

#### Personal life

James Goodnight first met his wife, Ann, during his senior year at [North Carolina State University](/North_Carolina_State_University), while she was attending [Meredith College](/Meredith_College). Their marriage, now spanning over five decades, has resulted in three children. Among them is James Goodnight Jr., a notable real estate redeveloper and proponent of historic preservation.

##### Rock collection

Goodnight possesses a profound and enduring interest in [rock collecting](/Amateur_geology). This fascination began in his childhood, where he would collect [quartzes](/Quartz) and [arrowheads](/Arrowheads) in the vicinity of Greensboro. He rediscovered this passion in adulthood, embarking on a journey to collect rare rocks and other geological specimens. His collection extends beyond mere minerals to include [fossilized wood](/Fossilized_wood), [dinosaur eggs](/Dinosaur_eggs), and arrowheads dating back to the [Archaic period in North Carolina](/Archaic_period_(North_America)) (approximately 8,000 BC to 1,000 BC). This extensive collection comprises hundreds of items sourced from over 40 countries worldwide. Goodnight himself has described rocks and minerals as a form of natural art.

Portions of his remarkable collection are displayed on the SAS campus in Cary, North Carolina. This exhibition has been lauded as "a testament to his love of unique pieces of earth, from petrified dinosaur eggs, to impressive, mosaic chunks of native granite, to large, glassy meteorites." Furthermore, Goodnight has generously loaned pieces from his collection to the [North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences](/North_Carolina_Museum_of_Natural_Sciences) for public appreciation. A curated selection of these pieces is featured in the Betsy M. Bennett Bridge to Discovery, a pathway connecting the museum to its Nature Research Center.

#### Wealth and philanthropy

As of April 2023, James Goodnight's net worth was estimated at US$7.4 billion, solidifying his position as the wealthiest individual in [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), surpassing even [Epic Games](/Epic_Games)' [Tim Sweeney](/Tim_Sweeney_(game_developer)). The [Bloomberg Billionaires Index](/Bloomberg_Billionaires_Index) subsequently placed his net worth at US$11 billion in April 2024.

Goodnight has demonstrated a deep commitment to improving the state of education, with a particular focus on elementary and secondary levels. He has been a vocal advocate for increased funding for [STEM](/STEM) education across the United States, aiming to combat [brain-drain](/Brain-drain) and prevent the outsourcing of critical research and technology jobs to other nations. In 1996, Goodnight, his wife Ann, and his business partners [John Sall](/John_Sall) and Ginger Sall, established [Cary Academy](/Cary_Academy), an independent preparatory school. He has also actively championed the restructuring of [preschool](/Preschool) funding in North Carolina to broaden access for more children within the state.

The Goodnights have made significant philanthropic contributions to North Carolina State University. They established the Goodnight Scholarships, which encompass the Goodnight Scholars Program and the Goodnight Transfer Scholars Program. These initiatives provide comprehensive scholarships, including full tuition, and robust development programs specifically for students pursuing STEM fields. Their endowments have also been instrumental in creating the Goodnight Doctoral Fellowship, funding 28 named faculty positions, and establishing a deanship at North Carolina State University.

The Goodnights founded the Goodnight Educational Foundation in 2005. This foundation has been a key supporter of the North Carolina Independent Colleges and Universities' Science of Reading Initiative. In 2023, a $1.5 million endowment from the foundation established the Goodnight Distinguished Professorship in Early Literacy at [Western Carolina University](/Western_Carolina_University). Goodnight has also lent his support to the [William and Ida Friday Institute for Educational Innovation](/William_C._Friday).

Beyond education, the Goodnights have also contributed to causes focused on [wildlife conservation](/Wildlife_conservation) and historical preservation. They sponsored the Jim and Ann Goodnight Museum Park, an integral part of the [North Carolina Museum of Art](/North_Carolina_Museum_of_Art) in [Raleigh](/Raleigh,_North_Carolina). In 2018, the Goodnights were recognized by the [North Carolina Museum of History](/North_Carolina_Museum_of_History) for their dedicated efforts in preserving North Carolina's rich history. He is also a noted patron of the [Carolina Ballet](/Carolina_Ballet).

Both James and Ann Goodnight are deeply involved in the local community of [Cary, North Carolina](/Cary,_North_Carolina). Goodnight has made substantial real estate investments in Cary, which, in conjunction with the tax revenue generated by SAS and the influx of thousands of employees, has significantly fueled the town's growth since the 1970s. His investments have also extended to the development of the neighboring community of Chatham Park. He holds ownership of [Prestonwood Country Club](/Prestonwood_Country_Club) and The Umstead Hotel and Spa, both strategically located on the periphery of the SAS campus.

